---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CTASection from '../components/sections/CTASection.astro';
import { seo } from '../lib/seo';

const meta = seo(
  'Fees',
  'Meridian does not publish fixed rates. Fees are discussed transparently during the free initial consultation, before any commitment is made.',
  '/fees'
);
---

<BaseLayout
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  canonical={meta.canonical}
>
  <section class="container-narrow">
    <h1>Fees</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Meridian does not publish fixed rates. Dispute resolution does not
      lend itself to standardized pricing.
    </p>

    <p>
      The scope of a mediation engagement depends on the complexity of the
      dispute, the number of parties involved, the volume of preparation
      required, and the number of sessions needed to reach resolution. A
      straightforward two-party commercial dispute and a multi-beneficiary
      estate conflict are fundamentally different in scope — and pricing
      that pretends otherwise would be misleading.
    </p>

    <h2>What to Expect</h2>
    <p>
      Fees are discussed transparently and agreed upon during the initial
      consultation, before any commitment is made to proceed. You will
      know exactly what the engagement involves — and what it will cost —
      before you decide whether to move forward.
    </p>
    <p>
      There is no fee for the initial consultation. It exists to assess
      your situation, determine whether mediation is appropriate, and give
      you the information you need to make that decision.
    </p>

    <h2>Cost Relative to Litigation</h2>
    <p>
      Mediation is, in most cases, significantly less expensive than
      litigation or arbitration — and faster. The goal is not simply to
      be cheaper, but to resolve disputes more efficiently and with outcomes
      that the parties themselves have shaped. Those outcomes tend to be
      more durable than imposed decisions.
    </p>

    <h2>How Fees Are Structured</h2>
    <p>
      Fees are typically structured on a session or engagement basis,
      depending on the matter. Where parties share the cost of mediation
      equally — which is common — that arrangement is confirmed in writing
      at the outset.
    </p>
  </section>

  <CTASection
    title="Discuss fees during a free consultation"
    body="No rates are committed to before you have a clear picture of the process and what your matter involves."
  />
</BaseLayout>
